1550-1546 Broadway, at, adjoining and south of the S.E. corner of West 46th Street. The corner building No. 1550, is also known as No. 168 West 46th Street. This section of Times Square is technically Seventh Ave., but the buildings bear Broadway numbers.

West 46th Street, south side, west from, (No. 236) a point midway between Broadway and Eighth Ave., to the latter. Shown is the rear of the Imperial Theatre which has an entrance at No. 249 West 45th Street. West of same is a row of 3-story brownstone houses that bear Nos. 256 to 262. At the S.E. corner of Eighth Ave., is the Hotel Fulton, bearing Nos. 266-268 West 46th Street and No. 740-42 Eighth Ave. This set consists of a negative and a positive.

1539-1449 Broadway, at the S.W. corner of West 46th Street, showing the entrance to the Gaity Theatre through this building. On the left and only partially seen, is the Astor Theatre which is located at the N.W. corner of West 45th Street. This set consists of a negative and a positive view.

September 1935.

W.P.A. Photo.

Broadway, west side, north from W. 46th (left) to 47th (right) Streets, showing low structures on this Times Square frontage. The H & H Automat is flanked by the Globe and Central Theatre entrances which are easily distinguishable by the marquees. In the center of this block and this side of Eighth Avenue are the Paramount, and the Edison Hotels, facing on 47th and 46th Streets respectively. The photographer is viewing northwestward towards same from a vantage point at No. 145 W. 45th Street.

August 9, 1935.

P.L. Sperr

Times Square at West 46th Street, showing Broadway (left) converging with Seventh Ave. (right) at West 47th Street (apex). This view is north-ward and shows W.P.A. employees removing the Seventh Ave. car tracks.

July 14, 1936.

W.P.A. photo.
Federal Art Project.

Times Square, north from West 46th Street, showing W.P.A. employees repairing a triangular safety zone. Broadway (left) and Seventh Ave. (right) intersect at this point with a common apex (building, with sign atop) at 47th Street.

August 13, 1936.

W.P.A. Photo.

Times Square: A northward view from West 46th Street, showing the northern apex with the recently dedicated monument to Father Duffy of the 69th Regiment there. North of 47th Street., Broadway (left) and Seventh Ave. (right) regain their identity. This is a set of two views; No. 2 of which is photographed from the Seventh Ave. side.

September 14, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
